Ansible Lab 1 - Localhost Setup and Basic Playbook
Overview

This lab demonstrates:

Installing Ansible on Ubuntu
Creating an Ansible project structure
Configuring localhost inventory
Testing Ansible connectivity
Writing a simple playbook
Understanding check mode (-C)
Learning playbook syntax and indentation
Step 1 - Install Ansible

Update the system packages:

sudo apt update
sudo apt upgrade -y

Install Ansible:

sudo apt install ansible -y

Verify installation:

ansible --version
Step 2 - Create Project Folder Structure

Create folders for Ansible scripts and labs:

mkdir ansible-scripts
cd ansible-scripts/

mkdir lab-1
cd lab-1/

Example terminal output:

ubuntu@ip-172-31-41-98:~$ mkdir ansible-scripts
ubuntu@ip-172-31-41-98:~$ cd ansible-scripts/
ubuntu@ip-172-31-41-98:~/ansible-scripts$ mkdir lab-1
ubuntu@ip-172-31-41-98:~/ansible-scripts$ cd lab-1/
ubuntu@ip-172-31-41-98:~/ansible-scripts/lab-1$
Step 3 - Configure Ansible Inventory

Create inventory file:

nano inventory.ini

Add the following content:

[local]
localhost ansible_connection=local
Step 4 - Test Connection to Localhost

Run Ansible ping module:

ansible -i inventory.ini local -m ping

Expected output:

localhost | SUCCESS => {
    "changed": false,
    "ping": "pong"
}
Step 5 - Create Playbook

Create playbook file:

nano playbook.yml

Add the following content:

---
- name: Test
  hosts: local

  tasks:
    - shell: echo "Hello Ansible!"

    - shell: ls -la /home/ubuntu/

    - shell: echo "Test" > /tmp/test.txt

    - shell: whoami
Step 6 - Run Playbook
Dry Run / Check Mode
ansible-playbook -C playbook.yml -i inventory.ini
Actual Execution
ansible-playbook playbook.yml -i inventory.ini
Notes
1. Shell Module

The shell module is used to execute Linux bash commands.

Example:

- shell: whoami
2. Check Mode (-C)

-C means:

Check mode
Dry run mode
Simulates changes without applying them

Example:

ansible-playbook -C playbook.yml -i inventory.ini
3. Stateful Commands in Check Mode

Some commands that modify system state may be skipped in check mode.

Example:

rm inventory.ini

This changes system state permanently, so Ansible may skip it during dry run.

Problem Statement

Create an Ansible playbook to perform a simple local system health and setup check.

The playbook should:

Print a start message
Display current working directory
Show current date and time
Create a demo folder
Create a sample file inside the folder
Show the hostname of the machine
End Goal

By the end of this lab, learners should understand:

Basic Ansible playbook writing
YAML indentation and syntax
Inventory configuration
Task execution
Check mode (-C)
Localhost automation
Estimated Time

15 Minutes

Useful Commands
Verify Inventory
ansible all --list-hosts -i inventory.ini
Syntax Check
ansible-playbook --syntax-check playbook.yml -i inventory.ini
Verbose Execution
ansible-playbook -v playbook.yml -i inventory.ini
Folder Structure
ansible-scripts/
└── lab-1/
    ├── inventory.ini
    └── playbook.yml
